The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

NATION BRIEFS

 New Delhi, July 3: The home ministry has moved the Supreme Court seeking permission to make structural changes in and around the disputed structure at Ayodhya for security reasons.

 an application before the apex court, the ministry has submitted that there was a need to fortify the area by building a wall and cover the open space over the sanctum sanctorum with an iron mesh.

 The court had earlier barred all construction activities in the area.

 The ministry has reportedly told the court that there were intelligence inputs on terrorists planning another attack on the structure. 

 New Delhi: The Supreme Court on Monday refused to stay a Gujarat High Court order restraining the Centre from placing before Parliament the Justice U.C. Banerjee committee report on the Godhra train fire. 

 Chandigarh: The Congress high command has accepted former Haryana chief minister Bhajan Lals resignation as state party president. He had resigned citing disappointment over the pathetic condition of the common man under the Congress government led by Bhupinder Singh Hooda. 

 Calcutta: The Trinamul Congress will enjoy Opposition status in the Bengal Assembly till the Bongaon bypoll result is announced despite not having 10 per cent of the seats in the 294-member House. If Trinamul wins Bongaon, it will have 30 MLAs, which will ensure it Opposition status. The Speaker said the party would be allotted 45 per cent of the time reserved for the debate on the state budget.

 New Delhi: In the first visit by an Argentinian foreign minister in 12 years, Jorge Enrique Taiana landed in Mumbai on Monday with an 80-member team. He will go to Delhi on Wednesday.

 Calcutta: Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee will meet leaders of alliance partner CPI on Tuesday to clear their doubts about the governments industry policy. Along with commerce and industries minister Nirupam Sen, he had met RSP and Forward Bloc leaders on Sunday.




